%I A393426 #21 Apr 29 2026 15:15:13
%S A393426 1,24,24,24,120,24,336,24,72,120,1320,24,4368,336,120,48,1224,72,1368,
%T A393426 120,336,1320,1104,24,600,4368,216,336,9744,120,3720,96,1320,1224,
%U A393426 1680,72,50616,1368,4368,120,4920,336,56760,1320,360,1104,4512,48,2352,600,1224,4368,11448
%N A393426 Smallest k multiple of n such that the Pisano period A001175(k) divides k.
%C A393426 Let P = A001175.
%C A393426 a(n) exists for all n: we can prove that P(k) divides k for k = 4*lcm(1,2,...,n), n >= 3. Write k = 2^(e_1)*3^(e_2)*5^(e_3)*...*(p_i)^(e_i), then:
%C A393426  - For p_i != 2 or 5, P((p_i)^(e_i)) divides 2 * (p_i)^(e_i-1) * (p_i-Legendre(p_i,5)) = 4 * (p_i)^(e_i-1) * (p_i-Legendre(p_i,5))/2. Since both (p_i)^(e_i-1) and (p_i-Legendre(p_i,5))/2 divide lcm(1,2,...,n), we have that P((p_i)^(e_i)) divides k;
%C A393426  - For p_i = 5, P(5^(e_3)) = 4*5^(e_3) divides k;
%C A393426  - For p_i = 2, P(2^(e_1)) = 3*2^(e_1-1) divides k.
%C A393426 Note that if n | k and P(k) | k, then P(n) | P(k) | k, so lcm(n,P(n)) | k. As a result, to obtain a(n), we start with n and apply continuously the iteration n -> lcm(n,P(n)). Here the iteration must halt because n dividing a(n) implies lcm(n,P(n)) dividing lcm(a(n),P(a(n))) = a(n). We will finally reach some fixed point k0 dividing a(n) such that n divides k0 and P(k0) divides k0, and then that k0 must be a(n) since a(n) is the smallest number with the property that n divides k and P(k) divides k.
%C A393426 By comments in A317971, a(n) is divisible by 24 for n > 1, so a(n) = a(2*n) = a(3*n) = a(4*n) = a(6*n) = a(8*n) = a(12*n) = a(24*n) for n > 1.
%H A393426 Jianing Song, <a href="/A393426/b393426.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A393426 a(13) = 4368 is the smallest k divisible by 13 such that A001175(k) divides k. Indeed, we have A001175(4368) = 336.
%e A393426 a(73) = 3694968 is the smallest k divisible by 73 such that A001175(k) divides k. Indeed, we have A001175(3694968) = 50616.
%o A393426 (PARI) \\ Pisano period of k
%o A393426 P(k) = {
%o A393426 \\ find maximum possible order
%o A393426 my(r=1, f=factor(k));
%o A393426 for(j=1, #f[, 1], my(p=f[j, 1], e=f[j, 2]);
%o A393426     if(p%5==1||p%5==4, r=lcm(r,(p-1)*p^(e-1)));
%o A393426     if(p%5==2||p%5==3, r=lcm(r,2*(p+1)*p^(e-1)));
%o A393426     if(p==5, r=lcm(r,4*5^e));
%o A393426 );
%o A393426 my(ld=divisors(r), d); for(i=1, #ld, d=ld[i]; if(Mod([1,1;1,0],k)^d==[1,0;0,1], return(d)));
%o A393426 }
%o A393426 a(n) = my(s=P(n)); while(n%s!=0, n=lcm(n,s); s=P(n)); n
%Y A393426 Cf. A001175, A235249 (fixed point of n->A001175(n)), A317971.
%K A393426 nonn,new
%O A393426 1,2
%A A393426 _Jianing Song_, Apr 26 2026
